Orchestrates a full summarization run over an abstract `Fs` + `Agent`: writes one `.ctx` file per leaf source file, then walks affected directories leaf-up (deepest first, repo root last) writing `rollup.ctx` per directory. `intent.md` files are read as rollup input but never written by this file.

The core sequencing fact: `run_with_prompts` first summarizes *all* leaves, then computes `affected_dirs(targets)` and summarizes rollups in that fixed leaf-up order — each rollup's prompt input (`assemble_rollup_input`) is assembled by re-reading whatever `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files currently exist on `fs` for that directory's children, so it depends on earlier writes in the same run having already landed; reordering the loop breaks correctness silently rather than erroring. `affected_dirs` computes every ancestor directory of every target via `cpath::ancestor_dirs`, dedupes with a `BTreeSet`, then sorts by `(-depth, name)` — repo root (`depth 0`, `""`) is always last. `dir_label` maps `""` to `"."` only for display in the prompt text, not for path construction.

`assemble_rollup_input` skips `rollup.ctx` and `intent.md` when scanning a directory's context-dir children, includes `.ctx`-suffixed files as leaf sections, and for non-`.ctx` entries checks for a nested `rollup.ctx` (i.e. subdirectories) and inlines that instead — so it silently ignores subdirectories that have no rollup yet (no error, just omission). Path construction relies on `cpath::context_dir_of`, `cpath::intent_of`, `cpath::rollup_of`, and `cpath::leaf_ctx`/`cpath::ancestor_dirs` from the sibling `cpath` module — the on-disk `.ctx`/rollup layout convention lives there, not here.

`summarize_leaf` enforces access control before reading: `cpath::validate_rel` rejects unsafe relative paths, and `ctx_core::access::deny_reason(src, fs.is_ignored(src)?)` gates ignored/denied targets, returning `SummError::AccessDenied` with the reason — this is the only place in the module that checks gating; `summarize_rollup` has no equivalent check and trusts its caller.

`scope_check(count, approve) -> Result<(), SummError>` is a pure guard (not wired to any fs/agent call here) that blocks runs touching more than `MAX_TARGETS` (50) targets unless `approve` is true; callers elsewhere must invoke this explicitly before calling `run`/`run_with_prompts`, since neither of those enforces it internally.

`load_prompts` reads `<prompts_dir>/summarizer-leaf.md` and `summarizer-rollup.md`, mapping any read failure to `SummError::MissingPrompt(path)` — the actual prompt text is never embedded in this crate. `run` loads prompts from `prompts_dir` via the same `fs`, while `run_with_prompts` accepts pre-loaded `Prompts` so the prompt source and the summarized tree can use different filesystem roots (documented as intentional decoupling, e.g. prompts from process cwd vs. a scanned target tree).